<p>The drum bearing is a component most people have never heard of until it fails. It sits at the rear of the drum and supports its weight through every rotation — thousands of cycles per load, year after year. When it wears out, you get a grinding or rumbling sound that starts low and gets progressively louder over weeks. We handle these calls across Los Angeles County, Orange County, and Ventura County regularly — from Beverly Hills to Newport Beach to Thousand Oaks. It's one of those repairs where calling us early makes a real difference in the final cost.</p>

<h2>Drum Bearing vs Drum Rollers — How to Tell the Difference</h2>
<p>This is the most common question we get on noise calls, and it matters because the repairs cost different amounts. Both worn bearings and worn <a href="/repairs/lg-dryer-drum-roller-replacement/">drum rollers</a> cause noise during operation, but the sound is different once you know what to listen for.</p>
<p>Worn drum rollers squeak or squeal — high-pitched, rhythmic, gets louder as the dryer warms up. You can sometimes quiet it briefly by pressing lightly on the drum through the door opening.</p>
<p>A worn drum bearing produces a deeper grinding or rumbling — more like something scraping under load, often constant rather than rhythmic. On some LG DLGX models we've seen in Pasadena and Glendale, the bearing noise has a metallic resonance that customers describe as the dryer "groaning." It's often worse at the start of a cycle when the drum is cold, then settles into a steady rumble once warmed up.</p>
<p>Two checks you can do before calling us. First: open the door, grab the drum, and push it gently toward the back of the machine. A worn rear bearing has noticeable play — the drum moves when it shouldn't. Second: look at the rear panel inside the drum for visible wear marks or scoring, or check around the door seal for metal shavings. Both of these tell us immediately how far the bearing has progressed.</p>
<p>One more symptom we see in Beverly Hills and Torrance service calls that people don't always connect to the bearing: clothes catching on something inside the drum, or the drum feeling unusually hot to touch after a cycle — that's the bearing friction generating excess heat. If your dryer has started snagging fabrics or the drum area runs hotter than usual, the bearing is worth checking.</p>

<h2>Warning Signs That Need Immediate Attention</h2>
<p>If your LG dryer makes metal-on-metal scraping sounds, emits a burning smell during operation, shows error codes related to drum rotation, or the drum stops completely mid-cycle — shut it off and call us. We've seen cases in Pasadena and Santa Monica where homeowners continued running the dryer through these symptoms. The bearing seized completely and damaged the drum housing, turning a standard bearing replacement into a full drum replacement on top. That's a $600+ job instead of a $320 one. The grinding sound is the dryer telling you something — it's worth listening.</p>

<h2>The Repair</h2>
<p>Drum bearing replacement is one of the more labor-intensive dryer repairs we do — the bearing housing sits behind the drum assembly which means the drum has to come completely out. We pull the top and front panels, photograph the belt routing before we remove anything, disconnect the door switch harness, and lift the drum out. We remove the old bearing, clean the shaft and housing thoroughly, and press the new OEM unit in with correct alignment and torque.</p>
<p>While the drum is out we check the rollers, idler pulley, and belt. On a machine that's been running with a bad bearing for a while, the extra vibration and heat often accelerates wear on those parts too. We'll tell you what we find and quote any additional work separately before we proceed — you don't get surprised at the end.</p>
<p>Reassembly requires precise drum alignment within the cabinet — the drum has to sit correctly on the rollers or the new bearing wears unevenly from day one. We manually rotate the drum several times to confirm smooth tracking before we run the test cycle. Total time on-site is 90–120 minutes for most LG models. We don't leave until the grinding is completely gone.</p>

<h2>Why We Use Only OEM Bearings</h2>
<p>Aftermarket bearings use inferior bearing material with looser tolerances than LG's OEM specification. Our experience in Calabasas and Glendale is that aftermarket units fail in 12–18 months versus 8–12 years for OEM. The price difference is small. The reliability difference is significant. We stock OEM bearing assemblies for all major DLGX, DLEX, and DLE series and confirm the exact specification for your model before arrival.</p>

<h2>What It Costs</h2>
<p>Drum bearing replacement runs <strong>$320–400 total</strong> for most LG dryers. The OEM bearing assembly is $60–100 depending on the model. Labor is $220–280, which reflects the full disassembly, correct installation, inspection of rollers and belt while we're inside, and test cycle. The $65 diagnostic fee is waived when you approve the repair.</p>
<p>If rollers, belt, or idler pulley also need attention — common on machines that have been running with bearing noise for a while — we quote everything separately on-site before we proceed. Doing it all in one visit is always cheaper than separate calls.</p>
<p>A new comparable LG dryer starts around $800. At $320–400 with a 1-year warranty, bearing replacement makes clear sense on a machine that's otherwise in good shape. On a 12+ year old machine where we also find a failing <a href="/repairs/lg-dryer-heating-element-replacement/">heating element</a> or <a href="/repairs/lg-dryer-thermal-fuse-replacement/">thermal fuse</a> alongside the bearing, we'll walk you through the full picture honestly and let you decide whether repair makes sense. We're not going to push a $400 bearing replacement on a machine that's at the end of its life.</p>
